@tomriddle_1234 you could generate more **go routines** than cores and golang will distribute this as optimal as it can, however physically it is unlikely to get better performance. 
Regarding `select` there is a nice tour offered by golang.org: [select](https://tour.golang.org/concurrency/5). In simple words: `select` blocks until one of the cases are satsified, and then runs. Since `sumf` is a function that always waits for new data to come, it has to receive a signal to end, this is `endc`.
